\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:KS-stats"

\end_inset

 confirms that for an Itô diffusion, we cannot reject the hypothesis that
 exact sampler draws from the true distribution at the 
\begin_inset Formula $95\%$
\end_inset

 confidence level for a variety of initial distributions.
 Interestingly, the bridges produced by the exact sampler for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

-stable OU and Wiener processes are also generally of a high quality, suggesting
 that this method of simulating generalized bridges is fairly robust to
 the assumptions made in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "chap:2"

\end_inset

.
 As expected, the approximate sampler does not sample from the true distribution
 (we know this to be true for the Gaussian OU process, since it draws from
 the true bridge distribution conditional on the bridge being hit by an
 independent diffusion), and we note that the quality of the approximate
 sampler is inversely correlated with the computing time required to sample
 exact bridges.
 This is intuitive, highlighting a tradeoff between speed and quality, and
 formally expected: if the approximate sampler produces low quality samples,
 then the probability of such samples being hit by a hitting diffusion is
 low.
 Since the exact sampler accepts sample paths that are less likely to be
 hit by a hitting diffusion with higher probability, it must spend more
 time simulating hitting diffusions for any given proposal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While it is true that the approximate sampler formally does not sample from
 the true generalized bridge distribution, we show in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:q-q"

\end_inset

 that the approximate and exact samplers for the Gaussian OU bridges produce
 qualitatively high quality samples.
 In general, we see that the approximate samples are slightly thinner-tailed
 than the true distribution—conditional on the approximate samples being
 hit by a hitting process (which in this case mean-reverts to 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

), we would expect the approximate sample paths to tend toward 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 as well.
 The lowest quality approximate samples occur when 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{0}\sim\mbox{Expo}$
\end_inset

; the fatter tail and skewedness of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Expo}$
\end_inset

 distribution vis-à-vis the other initial distributions results in sample
 paths starting from relatively extreme values, reducing the probability
 of their intersection with a mean-reverting hitting process.
\end_layout

