\begin_layout Standard
In light of the qualitative similarity of the approximate and exact samplers,
 it is worth noting that the K-S statistics presented in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:KS-stats"

\end_inset

 represent the most liberal estimates of the deviation of the samples from
 the true distribution—in particular, the marginal distribution of the sampled
 bridges, whether approximate or exact, are the same as the unconstrained
 process at times 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\{0,1\}$
\end_inset

 by definition, and 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1/2$
\end_inset

 represents the point in time at which the marginal distributions of these
 bridges have the most freedom to deviate from the true distribution.
 Recalling that the MCEM algorithm proposed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "chap:EM"

\end_inset

 involves taking an expectation of an integral over an entire generalized
 bridge sample path, the K-S test on the marginal distribution of our approximat
ely sampled paths at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1/2$
\end_inset

 represents an overly stringent view on the usability of the approximate
 samples in the context of the proposed MCEM algorithm.
 In the next section, we demonstrate that an MCEM algorithm using the approximat
e bridge sampler produces comparable results to one using the exact bridge
 sampler.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Inference on Distributional Data
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Having verified our ability to sample 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

-bridges, in this section, we verify the correctness of the MCEM algorithm
 proposed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "chap:EM"

\end_inset

.
 We will focus conducting inference for the parameters governing a Gaussian
 OU process (OU diffusion), due to the prevalence of such processes as discussed
 above and their analytical tractability with regards to their K-L divergence
 from other Gaussian processes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our simulation strategy rests on the following observation: Consider a general
 stochastic process 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 with initial condition 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{0}=x_{0}$
\end_inset

 on the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{X}$
\end_inset

 is set to the distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 at times 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\{1/2,1\}$
\end_inset

, the proposed MCEM scheme under a Gaussian OU model initialized at 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 should converge to parameter which minimizes the K-L divergence of the
 OU diffusion at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\{1/2,1\}$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{X}$
\end_inset

 (note we pick 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2$
\end_inset

 for identifiability reasons).
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is also an OU diffusion, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 should simply converge to the parameters governing 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

; otherwise, so long as 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a Gaussian process, the K-L divergence is analytically available and
 we can compute what the true MKLD parameter ought to be.
 Note we can draw from any 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{X}$
\end_inset

 simply by simulating 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

 and taking its values at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\{1/2,1\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As an illustrative example, we choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=\nu_{X}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is an OU diffusion governed by parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta^{*}$
\end_inset

, and present the iterations of the MCEM algorithm under a OU diffusion
 model given 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:mcem-stationary"

\end_inset

.
 The proposed MKLDE should simply converge to 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta^{*}$
\end_inset

, and we wish to emphasize that the only 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

data
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 given to the algorithm is the ability to draw from 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

.
 Since the OU diffusion has a constant diffusion coefficient, the corresponding
 Lamperti transform is simply 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{\theta}(x)=x/\theta$
\end_inset

, and the requisite functions to perform MCEM can easily be worked out from
 the results in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "chap:EM"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

