\begin_layout Standard
With a heuristic sense of the dynamics of the MCEM's convergence, we present
 a comprehensive evaluation of the proposed algorithm to estimate the parameter
 vector for a Gaussian OU diffusion given a variety of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{X}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:diff-diffusions"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In particular, we consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{X}$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is an OU diffusion governed by 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta^{*}$
\end_inset

, a Wiener process, and a fractional Wiener process.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is equal to an OU diffusion, the MCEM algorithm should converge to 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta^{*}$
\end_inset

, bringing the K-L divergence of the distribution of an OU diffusion at
 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\{1/2,1\}$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{X}$
\end_inset

 to zero, since we have a correctly specified model.
 In the latter two cases, the MCEM algorithm can only minimize the K-L divergenc
e, as it is operating under model misspecification.
 On the other hand, when 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a Wiener process, the K-L divergence is minimized as 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\rightarrow(0,0,1)$
\end_inset

, since the OU diffusion reduces to a Wiener process in such a limit.
 Finally, when 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{H}$
\end_inset

 is a fractional Wiener process with Hurst parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

, the K-L divergence of the distribution of an OU diffusion governed by
 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\{1/2,1\}$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{X}$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{2}\left[\mbox{Tr}\left(\Sigma_{O}(\theta)^{-1}\Sigma_{F}(H)\right)+\log\frac{\det\Sigma_{O}(\theta)}{\det\Sigma_{F}(H)}-2\right],
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Sigma_{O}(\theta) & = & \frac{\sigma^{2}}{2\lambda}\begin{bmatrix}1-e^{-\lambda} & e^{-\lambda/2}-e^{-3\lambda/2}\\
e^{-\lambda/2}-e^{-3\lambda/2} & 1-e^{-2\lambda}
\end{bmatrix}\mbox{ and}\\
\Sigma_{F}(H) & = & \begin{bmatrix}2^{-2H} & 1/2\\
1/2 & 1
\end{bmatrix}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

are the covariance matrices of the values of an OU diffusion and a fractional
 Wiener process with Hurst parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 at times 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\{1/2,1\}$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 We choose 
\begin_inset Formula $H=0.2$
\end_inset

 so that the fractional Wiener process that mean reverts (preventing 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 from being bound at 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

), and numerically find the K-L divergence minimizing parameter to be 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{MKLD}=(0,0.832\dots,1.450\dots)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition to varying 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{X}$
\end_inset

, we also test the performance of the proposed MCEM scheme when we only
 have access to finitely many samples from 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{X}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, we compare the MCEM scheme when we can exactly sample from
 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{X}$
\end_inset

 an unlimited number of times (the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

asymptotic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 case) to a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

finite sample
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 case, where we resample a fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $100$
\end_inset

 samples from 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{X}$
\end_inset

 repeatedly.
 By the remarks in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "chap:EM"

\end_inset

, we expect that the MKLDE from the finite sample case should be less efficient,
 but still consistent for the true MKLD parameter.
 
