\begin_layout Standard
The reported standard deviations in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:diff-diffusions"

\end_inset

 capture the efficiency of the MKLDE, the variance inherent in the MCEM
 algorithm, and the variance of the DEoptim optimization procedure.
 As such, these standard deviations are far larger than they asymptotically
 ought to be with a sufficiently large number of MC samples and a sufficiently
 precise optimization procedure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In any case, we see that an MCEM scheme using either the approximate and
 exact samplers is consistent for the true MKLD parameter across all experiments
, up to a margin of error equal to the standard deviation of the MKLDEs.
 As expected, the finite sample experiments display lower efficiency but
 remain consistent, and using the exact sampler produces higher efficiency
 estimates in general.
 The approximate sampling scheme also appears to produce some bias in the
 estimation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 by producing thinner-tailed marginal distributions than the exact sampler,
 though given the variability of the MKLDEs, this bias does not appear to
 be significant.
 On the other hand, the computational time taken by using exact generalized
 bridge samples in the MCEM scheme is on the order of two magnitudes longer
 than the time used by approximate sampling.
 We conjecture that for all but the most extreme of distributional data
 (i.e.
 conditioning a process which mean reverts to zero on a joint distribution
 with marginal distributions centered far from zero), an MCEM scheme relying
 on approximate generalized bridge sampling will provide parameter estimates
 of sufficiently high quality, especially given the variance of MCEM estimates
 and stochastic optimization methods in the first place.
\end_layout

